The first virtual service provider will be arriving in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The Czech mobile market is relatively developed and our service providers provide the same services as their Western European partners.
Nevertheless, there is something missing here - a virtual service provider that forces classic service providers to reduce their prices significantly.
Maybe it won't be for long.
On the Mobil.cz website, we have often written that Czech service providers are among the most expensive in Europe.
This has been confirmed by the ČTÜ, which has pointed out that the price of the text in the Czech Republic is more expensive than in the rest of the Union.
Following the last step of the European Commission, the regulation of roaming charges may lead to a conflicting situation - messages from some Czech mobile operators from abroad will be cheaper than from the domestics.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that really wants to fight.
This may sound controversial, since we also have three mobile networks and our penetration is well above 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators are happy to complain that the Czech market is highly competitive.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office, Pavel Dvołák, who has said several times before that there is no room for another service provider in the Czech Republic.
It may be true that the classic service provider may no longer have too much chance with its own network (although it would probably be difficult to find a frequency anymore).
But there is another option - the virtual service provider.
It was precisely the introduction of virtual service providers on the mobile market that led to a significant reduction in prices, which would then have to be addressed by the classic service providers.
In the meantime, even before the launch of large fish, such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile in Great Britain, we heard sounds similar to ours.
However, it has been demonstrated that such service providers have a place and can indeed be successful.
However, we do not have to go too far for an example.
In February this year, we informed you of the start-up of the Mobiling virtual service provider in Poland.
This service provider has not been able to obtain more than 100 000 customers in six months and become the fifth largest service provider there.
Meanwhile, behind the Mobilking is the Penta Financial Group, which is also owned by U:phone in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual service providers is the possibility of focusing on a much narrower target group.
In order to operate effectively, it requires far fewer customers than the traditional service provider.
It does not involve relatively high construction, mobile network operation and maintenance costs.
Virtual service providers in the world generally appear at low cost - offer cheap calls and text messages, which are often counterbalanced by less services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in Britain offers texting at least 50 percent cheaper than its competitors.
But as the example of Mobiling in Poland shows, it can be a pretty good move for a target group.
This service provider focuses specifically on men.
"The real men choose the Mobiling Service provider - who they like to trust," says David Seibert, CEO of the Mobil Entertainment Company operating this virtual service provider.
It is difficult to say whether a vision similar to that of Poland can work with us.
Miroslav Čepický, spokesperson of Vodafone, questions: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which the majority of virtual service providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively satisfactory from the point of view of the provision of services."
In the Czech Republic, there is no chance that mobile operators will be able to do so.
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual service provider in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobiling.
"We are talking about a successful expansion of this project, but in the Czech Republic, the negotiations do not seem very hopeful.
The launch of Mobilking takes place in other countries of our region," said Jana Studničková, spokesperson of the Penta Financial Group in her phone interview with Mobilcz.
This indirectly demonstrated that existing Czech mobile operators are not too much into this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do their utmost to ensure that no potential competition exists.
The GTS Nowera Group has not long been hiding its interest in the launch of a virtual service provider, which therefore wishes to take another step to make Telenica O2 a real competitor in the field of corporate customers.
"We are very interested in providing not only landline but also mobile telecommunications services to our customers.
And the sooner the better.
We have discussed this possibility repeatedly with all Czech mobile operators.
Some of them have already made progress in the negotiations," says Pavel Kaidl, the Group spokesperson.
Maybe this is a better time.
Unofficial information suggests that the first virtual service provider will be lucky by the end of the year.
However, his birth is surrounded by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"In this moment, we do not think that a full-value virtual service provider would have a place on the Czech market.
Contrary to the other markets, the Czech market is very special.
Until now, we have not been invited by a single subject offering a complex and serious project in this area," said Vlastimil Sršeň from Telefónica 02 Press Department.
The special situation of the Czech market is also referred to by the other operators.
Ms Kemrová, spokesperson of T-Mobile, with the exception of O2, adds: "We have not yet recorded any viable and bilateral business projects that could be based on further."
And he added, "On the T-Mobile network by the end of the year, it is unlikely that any virtual service provider will show up.
At this moment, there should be a specific agreement on our table so that we can think in such a short space of time."
Vodafone’s attention is rather directed towards meeting its 3G licence requirements.
Miroslav Čepický adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual service providers, particularly in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure sharing.
This is what we consider to be the most cost-effective for our customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to partner in building networks shared with the fast mobile internet."
Responsible offices - a string with service providers
Mobile service providers' procedures are easy to understand, and the entry of a new service provider would lead to an increase in competition, a reduction in prices and a decrease in their profits.
So why make it easier for us to enter such a competition?
When it is important for service providers, they can cooperate, and they can also witness the string of U-phones around the birth.
The highest pressure on ČTÜ is likely to be around the birth of the U-phone of T-Mobile.
This is confirmed by the information publicly available from the website of ČTU.
But right now, the U:phone comes with a good argument as to why we should not allow the entry of the virtual service provider.
Martina Kemrová added: "The environment of competition in the mobile market has recently been affected by access to the fourth mobile market.
In view of the nature of the Czech mobile market, it is evident that the entry of another player into the market and its services would be subject to high requirements."
However, given the attitude of mobile operators, the total lack of interest of the Czech regulatory authorities is absolutely amazing.
In the meantime, it is not just the attitude of the ČTU, which unfortunately, in the Czech Republic - unlike Great Britain and other developed countries - has no right to intervene in economic competition.
Only the Office of Competition is entitled to do so.
But the office is typical of the whole problem.
"The entry into the mobile market of a virtual service provider would only be possible after the conclusion of a contract between a mobile service provider and a virtual service provider for the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, since the offer of potential interested parties is unlikely to have been sufficiently interesting for traditional service providers," she mentioned, in response to our question about Kristian Chlapua, the external relations department of the Competition Office.
A declaration thus formulated by the representatives of the service providers would probably not surprise anyone.
However, from an office that should represent the interests of consumers and also ensure that no one is allowed to take advantage of their market situation, it is more than strange.
In particular, when Kristian Chalua adds: "In a foreign country, where virtual service providers generally operate, we can observe that their entry has contributed to the reduction in the price of mobile phone services."
However, it is unlikely that UOHS’ interests do not fall within the scope of the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and on price reductions.
In this case, it is indeed shocking that the reaction of the three mobile operators is quite tangible.
The question is, is it really just a coincidence? It's almost self-evident.
As in the filling stations, totally identical gas prices are probably only works of chance and hard competition.
"The Office did not discover the signs of the anti-competitive procedure in this case, so there is no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the service providers have a leading position, i.e. a proportionately higher responsibility for their market realities.
The tools needed to open up the mobile market for virtual service providers are likely to be lacking by the telecommunications regulator," Chalua mentioned.
Presentation of the market-leading situation is one of several points of dispute.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by ČTÚ, which means that telecommunications is the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, there is, of course, no Czech service provider in the leading position.
However, some legal experts also offer a different approach - the approval of the network operator is always necessary for the creation of a virtual service provider.
And the mobile service provider - relatively logically - has a monopoly on its own network.
So it is necessarily dominant in a particular segment.
But even if we do not accept this argument, it should be a minimum incentive for UOHS to act in a similar way to three mobile operators.
In the meantime, complaints from interested parties (including the already mentioned GTS Nevera company) show that they face very similar obstacles during negotiations with all service providers.
And shifting responsibility to ČTú is a relatively common trick in telecommunications, with which UOHS takes its hands off the whole case.
We've met with this in a few similar situations.
Unfortunately, in the text of the recently adopted Telecommunications Act, the extension of the powers of ČTU in the field of economic competition has not been possible in telecommunications, although many experts have hoped to improve the situation.
The representatives of the U.S.S.S. must know this well, but probably others are in their interests.
This works when no one's watching
Meanwhile, the operation of some kind of fake virtual service provider remains unnoticed, many of which are already operating in Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that issue their own mobile service price lists, but which are only partially public.
It is multilevel marketing companies.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only the selected ones.
The magic lies in the fact that the company acts as a classic customer against the provider, which orders a large amount of SIM card.
As a priority client, you will then receive special offers (and other discounts).
The problem is that all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar promotions from trading conditions.
"If there were cases that he was talking about, there could be a breach of the contractual terms that we would deal with and which could lead to the completion of cooperation with the company," Martina Kemrová replied to our question about this problem.
But it is unlikely that news about such activities would not have reached the responsible people of mobile operators.
In particular, thousands of customers may be mentioned for the three companies mentioned.
At the same time, no service provider protects against such a procedure.
Because they do not have negligible profits from the activities of these companies and, unlike real virtual service providers, they do not in particular threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns of possible problems: "The law allows similar speculations, however, only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They must also accept that the SIM card is not on their phone, so they cannot fully have it as the general customers of mobile operators."
But at least that's what the C.T.U. should be weird about.
In addition, another question arises for UOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes on similar procedures, why prevent the birth of a virtual service provider?
It should be added that UOHS has relatively strong powers to expose such activities and that, if it does not, it does not have to be satisfied with the explanation of the service providers that they have not provided any such evidence and that their trading conditions prohibit it.
When we won't be the most expensive
As has already been said in the text a few times, the entry of virtual service providers into the mobile market has led to a noticeable fall in the price of services.
In the meantime, in virtually all countries where virtual service providers were established, classic service providers sought to prevent their creation more or less.
The arguments they used were practically the same - too small, perhaps too satisfied, problems with the quality of services, etc.
However, in the developed countries, it was at these moments that regulators intervened, which in no way protected the interests of mobile operators but their customers.
Then it was either through formal measures or informal pressure that the first virtual service provider that was followed by others was created.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are giving the whole case to each other.
Based on our experience, we cannot rid ourselves of the impression that unclear competences are good for them in these cases.
But let's not give up the fight.
If the background information is good and the virtual service provider is indeed coming out soon, the Czech mobile market may re-launch.
If one of the providers allowed the creation of a virtual mobile service provider, it is difficult for UOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of additional interested parties.
And perhaps we will no longer make more expensive calls compared to the rest of Europe.
