For the first time on Wednesday, Prague transport company also delivers chips card
On Wednesday, 1 October 2008, she writes herself in the history of the Prague Transport Company, when the first passenger enters metros, trams and buses, who will have an electronic coupon in his pocket instead of a paper ticket.
The coupon is currently available for about 100,000 people with the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can buy a 30-day and 90-day and annual coupon (which will be valid from 1 January 2009) and save on their chip card at the information centers and offices of the Transport Company at Muzeum, M'stek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka metro stations.
Coupons can also be purchased via the Internet via the Transport Company www.dpp.cz website from yesterday.
The service was used by more than 400 customers until afternoon hours.
Those who start to use online commerce can permanently forget the station publishing windows, where they have had to make long lines on a regular basis.
The coupon can be purchased via the Internet and placed on the Opencard card in one of the thirteen accounts of the City Library.
"In these places passengers have at their disposal a counter with trained servers, who help interested people buy online and save their purchased coupons on their cards," said Martin Opatrný, project spokesperson.
In addition to the libraries, the electronic coupons will be saved on the Opencard in the self-service machines installed in some of the lobbys.
How do these machines look?
Red, the ticket operators are reminded, and the passengers may already have noticed them at Roztyly, Budějovicka, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská metro stations.
"There are now five of them in the city, but it should be eighty by the end of the year," added Opatrný.
Check the coupon instead of the driver
It's easy to manage machines starting tomorrow.
All you have to do is put the Opencard chip card in and the coupon you've paid before will be gone on its own.
The electronic coupons will be valid from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also in its vicinity.
So on trains and bus lines around the city from 300 to 499, with the main residents of the Central-Czech routes travelling to the capital.
"On the Prague integrated trains, the guide has been provided with card readers, which also help determine the validity of the coupons in the zone," explained the control of the line marks by Filip Drápal from the Ropid organization that established the Prague public transport schedule.
The busses around the city are equipped with card readers at the driver's register.
The driver must therefore not only show the chip card but also place the Opencard in the location specified on the cash register side.
This is how the driver checks the validity of the coupons.
"If, for example, the passenger needs to verify the validity of the coupons, it is easy to ask the driver to do so," added Drápal.
Passengers who don't use buses around the city and won't remember when their coupon expires can go again to self-service machines that save coupons.
The information on the validity of their documents is displayed here on the display of the equipment.
