Returning drunk drivers will be obliged to install "Alcolock"
The Ministry of the Interior would require the driver to install a device that would prevent the vehicle from starting if the driver is in a state of drunkenness or does not blow into it.
The proposal was presented in June and is now being dealt with by the Public Prosecutor’s Office, according to which the pilot project will last for one year.
As the aim of the project is to return to the market, the driver will have to take part in a retraining course on transport education.
In addition to the Department of Transport Safety, the pilot project is also the DGT and the Institute of Road Safety Technology (FITSA).
According to statistics, 30-75% of drivers arrested for driving several times are back in the car.
This would be prevented by Alcolock because the system connected to the vehicle determines the level of alcohol in the air. If it is larger than allowed, or if the driver has not inhaled at all, the system will not allow the car to start.
The cost of the over 1000 euro instrument would be borne by the offender.
A 2007 US study has shown that vehicles equipped with such instruments can reduce the number of infringements by up to 65% in the first year after installation.
In Spain, it is estimated that 115 people could be saved every year by this rule.
The measure focuses on infringements for two reasons: on the one hand, it is easier to prevent them from becoming criminal;
on the other hand, it is easier to introduce, since the implementation of the legal reform is in the normal course, while the necessary criminal reform would require a basic amendment to the law.
The instrument is not yet available on the Spanish market in any form of trade, although it has already been installed in some industrial and public service vehicles in experimental mode.
The House of Representatives will vote tomorrow on the initiative of the Spanish Socialist Labour Party, which calls for the installation of the system in school buses, for a French model.
