Blood is safe again
Yesterday, the Hema-Québec celebrated the tenth anniversary of its foundation. Madam President Francine Décary had good reason to celebrate because Hema-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood-sacrifice companies in the world.
Most importantly, he managed to regain people's trust, which was severely shaken by the scandal about infected blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As known, the national reserve of blood treated by the Canadian Red Cross blood service was infected with acquired immune deficiency syndromes (HIV) and hepatitis C viruses in the 1980s.
In February 1994, following the drama and general upheaval, the Government of Canada launched a formal investigation under the leadership of Judge Horace Krever with the aim of finding out the circumstances that led to the tragedy and making proposals to avoid future similar cases.
While Judge Krever has submitted his late report, some provinces have set up their own committee to plan a new blood management system for Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee carried out this task.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two blood services were established in Canada: one was Héma-Québec, serving Quebec, and the other was the Canadian Blood Management Company responsible for all the other provinces and two territories.
"When Hema-Québec began its activity in 1998, nearly 38% of people had confidence in Quebec's blood supply system", Dr. Decary recalls.
The situation was desperate.
"In the coming years, however, we managed to regain people's trust as a result of improving the safety of blood products and our work in this area."
But Dr. Décary doesn't forget that "trust is a very fragile thing".
Since the establishment of Hema-Québec on 28 September 1998, it has applied the precautionary principle.
During this period, a number of cases have been discovered in Europe where new variants of bovine disease, Creutzfeldt-Jakob, have also infected people - the doctor, who has been managing the company since its establishment in 1998.
"We had no reason to know if this disease was spreading by blood.
We therefore relied on one of the most important recommendations in the Krever and Gélineau reports, which means that if we are uncertain about this and there is a risk of developing a serious disease, we need to apply exclusion measures. In this case, Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, which causes brain changes, inevitably leads to death.
Therefore, in April 1999 we did not accept blood from individuals who have spent more than a month in the United Kingdom since 1980.
And for a few years, it was no doubt established that the disease spreads through blood.
This case convinced us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle."
In 1999, a technology appeared on the market that allows for a much more sensitive diagnosis of the HIV virus. This is a nucleic acid test (NAT), which is able to detect directly in the blood of blood donors, rather than antibodies to the virus on which the tests used were based.
With the help of the NAT test, we could shorten the window period from infection until the virus can be detected in the blood using our technical tools, explains the expert.
This period could be reduced for a shorter period than a week.
Thus, the risk of blood transfusions not knowingly infecting the bloodstream has been significantly reduced and cannot be detected.
These developments greatly reduced the risk of AIDS spreading through blood transfusions.
Today, the risk of someone getting HIV-infected blood is 12 million to 1.
"In other words, it means that we should distribute 12 million blood products until someone is infected with the HIV virus.
Since Hema-Québec distributes 400-500 thousand blood products every year, it would take more than 24 years for a case like this to happen, and someone should be infected with HIV virus through a blood preparation.
I think that anyone today can accept or write blood transfusions to restore health - he is the number one leader of the Hema-Québec.
"The challenge of the next decade will be to maintain the reliability of our products.
We'll never know what a new pathogen is entering the system.
It was only last year that the chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, can enter the blood with an insect bite.
That is why we need to be constantly alert," Dr. Décary continued and then stressed that, apart from emergency supplies, Hema-Québec should provide sufficient permanent reserves.
"As the population age increases, so do the needs.
Because anticancer treatments have become more aggressive, patients often need to replace red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population has an impact on the blood tax population, as the number of people on the network who can donate blood accounts for only 3% of the people in Quebec.
However, every healthy person of at least 18 years of age who fulfils the suitability criteria can blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average 14% of applicants do not accept blood because, for example, they are infected with AIDS or malaria, and those who have been in a country where malaria destroys are not eligible for blood for a year.
"We have three percent of the reserve to meet the needs of the hospitals.
It's very rare for us to run out of supplies.
However, we need to increase the number of donors to the extent that existing ones age, because after a while they can't give blood.
However, it is very difficult to convince people to give blood, but it is even more difficult to keep them and to force them to become regular donors of blood.
In this world of running times today, there is hardly one hour left for a man to give blood," says Francine Décary.
The Héma-Quebec, which has an annual budget of USD 297 million, provides not only blood products, but also human tissues, such as bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin tissue, which are used almost exclusively for severely burned individuals.
These tissues are analyzed, converted and frozen, and then placed at Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public stem cell bank in Quebec.
The hair can only be obtained from the cord treated as medical waste, which allows for the treatment of severe diseases (e.g. leukaemia) in stem cells.
"We celebrated some weeks ago that our bank had entered into the model of a thousand cord blood cells, and every year we plan to remove more than a thousand new samples.
At the beginning of next year, we are probably starting to offer these for organ transplants," said Dr. Décary, who said that the umbilical cord-absorbing program is very popular today.
"Many mothers are sad because there is no possibility of doing so" - indeed so, as Hema-Québec does not have a way to make this complex and costly program available in every hospital in Quebec.
