Wall Street rescue - A deal between Democrats and Republicans
The leaders of the Bush government and the Republican and Democrat Congress finally agreed yesterday on an economic rescue measure, which has been the biggest plan since the great economic crisis in the 1930s.
The USD 700 billion plan to contain the financial crisis on Wall Street for months still needs to be approved by the two houses of Congress.
Key elements of the plan: more effective monitoring of implementation by representatives; new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of planned public funds; new provisions to keep the number of buildings occupied due to non-payments; access to the payment of the managers of the assisted companies.
Henry Paulson, U.S. Secretary of Finance, Nancy Pelosi, President of the American House and Judd Gregg, Republican representative in the trial yesterday, a few minutes before midnight, announced the good news after the two-day marathon trial was over.
"We have made great progress towards a solution that will work effectively on the markets," said Henry Paulson, a representative of the Bush Government.
"We have done everything in our power to save the real economy and American citizens from the current crisis on Wall Street," explained the Democrat representative.
"The most important aspect is that if we don't do this, then the shock, chaos and confusion in the everyday lives of the Americans will be huge," said the Republican representative Judd Gregg.
The trial was speeded up in the last few hours, fearing that another failure would damage the mood of investors.
They gave themselves a deadline for the agreement until the stock exchange opened this morning.
The two presidential candidates who joined the negotiations late showed themselves willing to reach an agreement, however, they are not pleased that the situation has increased to the end.
Senator Barack Obama gave himself the opportunity to expand the agreement with elements such as provisions relating to the preservation of the property or the payment of the heads of companies assisted by the State.
"When we ask taxpayers to take certain extraordinary steps on account of the irresponsibility of other people, it is not a pleasure.
These steps, however, are necessary," he noted on an American television show.
And when John McCain, the opponent, asked another channel if he would vote in favour of the proposed plan, he replied, "I would love to know the details, but I hope so."
"What I've read in large lines is that it's something that we all have to digest and that we can move on.
The possibility of doing nothing is simply unacceptable," he said.
According to the $700 billion plan, taxpayers' money would be used to purchase the dubious claims of American financial institutions, something at risk of unsold assets.
The plan was preceded by a 14-month crisis that started by the depreciation of the real estate loan, leading first to the collapse of risky real estate loans (second-hand mortgage loans) and then to the spread of other (trade) debt securities and finally to the freeze of liquid resources and to the upheaval of banks and financial institutions.
The first draft agreement was dropped by a group of Republican Members last week.
It seems that we've been able to get out of this dead end since the Democrats agreed to ensure that some of the 'toxic' tools of companies in difficulty are provided by the government rather than purchased by them.
In order to ensure that all members of Congress are satisfied, a provision has been included in the plan, which requires that if the government has to bear losses for five years under the programme, it may impose new taxes in order to recover its resources.
As part of the new plan, a USD 250 billion instalment would first be paid; this could be followed by another USD 100 billion if the President considers it necessary.
The remaining USD 350 billion should be approved by Congress with another vote.
In return for the assistance, Washington will acquire a share in the supported companies, which will result in a dividend of profits and which can be sold after the crisis has resolved.
The Federal Government will have the opportunity to delay the reservation of the property to cover the mortgage loans covered by the plan and to set the maximum amount of remuneration and compensation available to the managers of the companies affected by the crisis.
The planmakers would like the plan to be voted by the House of Representatives today and the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite their efforts, however, it is still not certain that the plan will be approved.
The statement against the plan was repeated yesterday among both the Republicans and Democrats.
"It is quite clear that Washington will not hear your voice" - said Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the financial committee of the house.
"Yes, we have serious financial problems.
Yes, there are solutions.
But there's no such thing as a way for taxpayers."
Brad Sherman, a Democrat leader of the small assembly called the 'Septical Group', presents things differently, but it comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred excellent economic experts, including three Nobel Prize-winning scientists, wrote to us to ask for Congress: don't hurry up and look carefully at the path she chooses," Sherman said yesterday.
In Europe, at the same moment, it was understood again that this is a global crisis.
After a crisis meeting, the three Benelux states announced that they would state part of the Fortis banking group at the value of EUR 11.2 billion (16.3 billion US dollars).
The intervention of the Governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French BNP Paribas announced that it would not buy out its competitors on the edge of the bankruptcy after losing EUR 2 million (U.S. USD 2.9 billion) as a result of the US crisis of secondary mortgage loans.
With its 85 thousand employees, Fortis is one of the 20 largest European banks and ten largest insurance companies.
"It's not thrown out money," said Dutch Minister of Finance Wouter Bos yesterday.
"In return, we'll acquire voting rights and influence at the bank.
This is exactly what depositors and households appreciate now that the situation is promising."
Meanwhile, on the other side of the La Manche, the British Government seems to be preparing to renationalise a new bank that has been hit by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take over the total amount of ongoing loans from Bradford and Bringley Bank, of which real estate loans amount to £41 billion (U.S. $75.5 billion).
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that they would purchase the British bank's subsidiaries and client base.
After this Northern Rock, Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank the British government has wanted to state since the beginning of the crisis.
