Psychology of overlicitation: Why are we giving more money?
In auctions, buyers tend to issue more money, overestimate the goods.
The neurological-economic foundations of this known - and seemingly irrational - behavior have been revealed to neurologists and economists at the University of New York.
According to their study in the magazine Science, people do not want to fall under a type of competition, such as eBay’s auction, so they pay too much for it.
The research tried to map this "play" nervous system pattern with the help of experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers was lotteryed and another group participated in the player auction while the active brain areas of experimental subjects were examined using the functional magnetic resonant (fMRI).
In both games, the participants may have won money, but in the course of the auction game - in which the overlicitation of the other party - the substria complex under the striatum has been intensively activated when the game was lost.
In addition to several other functions, this area of the brain plays a role in the mechanism of the nervous system's self-remuneration.
Therefore, researchers believe that the price rise can be explained by avoiding a violent reaction to the striatium.
To support their theory, the research group's economists also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this three groups were biding against a partner under different circumstances.
The control group was simply told how much of the real value of the product concerned and they made their bets.
In addition, another group was promised that if they get out of the game, they'll be able to win another $15.
The third group, on the other hand, received 15 dollars before the auction, but the group members lost this money in the event of a loss of auction.
The difference between the two groups was therefore merely that for one of them, the loss was stressed and for the other.
However, by demonstrating the hypotheses of neurologists, the members of the team who played against "loss" were willing to be higher than the control and winning groups.
"These results cannot be derived from any pre-existing economic theory.
So far, they have only explained the phenomena of the auction with the joy of victory and the risk-freeness.
Only the neurological imaging methods helped to solve the contradiction between these two theories, with a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should we seek medical advice?
About half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and among the leading causes of death in Hungary, chronic liver disease is mentioned.
The number of domestic hepatitises can be set at 100 per cent, but only seven thousand are treated for this reason: patients often do not know that they are infected.
The name of hepatitis is a common name of the liver caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities in their symptoms, characterised by inflammation of the liver and yellowness, but their pathogens and the diseases caused are different.
Hepatitis viruses are spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E via the food channel (e.g. infected food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body fluids (donda, vaginal discharge, saliva).
Travellers should be vaccinated against virus A and B, and there is no vaccine against C.
Hepatitis Symptoms appear two or three weeks after the intake of infected food, generally accompanied by malaise, weakness, abdominal discomfort, nausea.
The yellowing on the skin and on the white of the eyes, the stools become clear, the urine becomes dark, and healing may take two to three weeks.
One million people worldwide die of the more severe type of disease, liver cancer caused by hepatitis B, and liver cancer.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten infected patients will receive medication.
Hepatitis C may also have very serious consequences: if not treated, it may lead to hepatic shrinking and liver cancer.
Most infected people don't even know about their disease, because the pathogen will sublimely destroy their liver cells, and in many cases the first symptoms will appear after 20-30 years.
It is therefore very important to prevent early and carry out regular screenings.
In three groups, this disease is much more than average: people who have had blood transfusions before 1991, drug users and tattoos.
The number of people infected with chronic hepatitis C virus is currently 200 million in the world.
Since the disease may already be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is worth contacting your doctor if you experience any symptoms of unknown origin.
In time, the disease can be cured, the virus can be removed from the body, thus eliminating the potential for infection and preventing the development of cancer.
30 September is the World Day for Hepatitis, which was first organised in 2004 by organisations representing patients around the world.
Its aim is to raise awareness of the causes of chronic hepatitis caused by viruses and the importance of early detection of the disease.
